WEBVTT

02:36.356 --> 02:38.950
[hubbub]

02:39.026 --> 02:41.825
[munches]

02:41.895 --> 02:46.526
- Ah. It was a fine meal.
- Yes, it was, wasn't it?

02:46.600 --> 02:48.193
Yes, what should we do now?

02:48.268 --> 02:52.034
- Let's have lunch.
- Oh, good idea.

02:52.105 --> 02:54.073
Quiet down, you villains.

02:54.141 --> 02:56.701
[pumpkin] I'm being stolen.
Help me, help me!

02:56.777 --> 02:58.643
[Pumpkin] Put me down!

02:58.712 --> 03:01.147
[children chatter]

03:01.215 --> 03:02.444
Hello.

03:03.650 --> 03:05.140
[dog barks]

03:08.622 --> 03:10.420
What about my nose?

03:10.490 --> 03:11.480
[Yelps]

03:13.026 --> 03:15.620
[woman, cackling]
Banana peels coming down!

03:17.965 --> 03:20.957
Come along, ladies.
Here's a nice Christmas turkey.

03:21.034 --> 03:23.799
Turkey.
Get your Christmas turkey.

03:23.870 --> 03:27.101
Hey, get back in the box, Martin!

03:27.174 --> 03:31.077
Get your boomerang fish.
Guaranteed fresh.

03:31.144 --> 03:35.138
Throw the fish away
and it comes back to me.

03:35.215 --> 03:36.979
Get 'em while they're fresh.

03:37.050 --> 03:39.144
- Christmas apples.
- We got Macintosh.

03:39.219 --> 03:41.187
- Christmas apples.
- Red Delicious.

03:41.255 --> 03:43.155
Tuppence apiece, while they last.

03:43.223 --> 03:46.420
We... They won't last long
the way you're eating them.

03:46.493 --> 03:49.258
I'm creating scarcity.
Drives the prices up.

03:49.329 --> 03:51.263
- Rizzo...
- [Rizzo clears throat]

03:51.331 --> 03:55.234
Hello. Welcome to
the Muppet Christmas Carol.

03:55.302 --> 03:57.031
I am here to tell the story.

03:57.104 --> 03:58.868
And I am here for the food.

03:58.939 --> 04:00.737
My name is Charles Dickens.

04:00.807 --> 04:02.798
And my name is Rizzo the Rat.

04:02.876 --> 04:05.573
Wait a second,
you're not Charles Dickens.

04:05.646 --> 04:06.875
I am, too.

04:06.947 --> 04:09.939
A blue furry Charles Dickens
who hangs outwith a rat?

04:10.017 --> 04:11.143
Absolutely.

04:11.218 --> 04:14.017
Charles Dickens
was a 19th century novelist.

04:14.087 --> 04:15.316
A genius.

04:15.389 --> 04:17.187
You are too kind.

04:17.257 --> 04:19.156
Why should I believe you?

04:19.226 --> 04:22.821
Because I know the story of <i>A</i> Christmas
Carol like the back of my hand.

04:22.896 --> 04:25.092
- Prove it.
- All right.

04:25.165 --> 04:27.532
There's a little mole on my thumb.

04:27.601 --> 04:31.094
And a scar on my wrist
from when I fell off my bicycle...

04:31.171 --> 04:34.106
No, don't tell us your hand,
tell us the story.

04:34.174 --> 04:36.268
Oh, thank you. Yes.

04:36.343 --> 04:39.472
The Marleys were dead,
to begin with.

04:39.546 --> 04:40.741
The... Pardon me?

04:40.814 --> 04:42.543
That's how the story begins,

04:42.616 --> 04:45.017
"The Marleys were dead,
to begin with."

04:45.085 --> 04:47.520
As dead as a doornail.

04:47.587 --> 04:50.989
It's a good beginning.
It's creepy and kind of... spooky.

04:51.058 --> 04:53.755
- Thank you, Rizzo.
- You're welcome, Mr. Dickens.

04:53.827 --> 04:56.592
In life, the Marleys had been
business partners

04:56.663 --> 05:01.066
with a shrewd moneylender
named Ebenezer Scrooge.

05:01.134 --> 05:04.229
You will meet him
as he comes around that corner.

05:04.304 --> 05:05.601
- Where?
- There.

05:05.672 --> 05:07.766
- When?
- Now.

05:09.710 --> 05:13.169
[Dickens] There he is,
Mr. Ebenezer Scrooge.

05:17.250 --> 05:20.550
Say, is it getting cold around here?
[shudders]

05:26.026 --> 05:28.825
<i>♪ When a cold wind blows,
it chills you</i>

05:28.895 --> 05:30.886
<i>♪ Chills you to the bone</i>

05:30.964 --> 05:33.456
<i>♪ But there's nothing in nature
that freezes your heart</i>

05:33.533 --> 05:35.524
<i>♪ Like years of being alone</i>

05:35.602 --> 05:38.401
<i>♪ It paints you with indifference</i>

05:38.472 --> 05:40.804
<i>♪ Like a lady paints with rouge</i>

05:40.874 --> 05:43.309
<i>♪ And the worst of the worst,
the most hated and cursed</i>

05:43.377 --> 05:45.709
<i>♪ ls the one that we ca" Scrooge</i>

05:45.779 --> 05:48.214
<i>- Unkind as any
- I And the wrath of many</i>

05:48.281 --> 05:50.306
<i>♪ This is Ebenezer Scrooge</i>

05:50.384 --> 05:55.322
<i>♪ There goes Mr. Humbug
There goes Mr. Grim</i>

05:55.389 --> 05:58.017
<i>♪ If they gave a prize for being mean</i>

05:58.091 --> 06:00.185
<i>♪ The winner would be him</i>

06:00.260 --> 06:02.285
<i>♪ Old Scrooge, he loves his money</i>

06:02.362 --> 06:05.161
<i>♪ 'Cause he thinks it gives him power</i>

06:05.232 --> 06:11.228
<i>♪ If he became a flavor
You can bet he would be sour</i>

06:11.304 --> 06:13.568
Even the vegetables don't like him.

06:15.308 --> 06:19.768
<i>♪ There goes Mr. Skinflint
There goes Mr. Greed</i>

06:20.247 --> 06:24.912
<i>♪ The undisputed master
of the underhanded deed</i>

06:24.985 --> 06:27.044
<i>♪ He charges folks a fortune</i>

06:27.120 --> 06:29.817
<i>♪ For his dark and drafty houses</i>

06:29.890 --> 06:32.222
<i>♪ Us poor folk live in misery</i>

06:32.292 --> 06:35.785
<i>♪ It's even worse for mouses</i>

06:35.862 --> 06:39.389
Please, sir, I want some cheese.

06:39.466 --> 06:42.026
<i>♪ He must be so lonely</i>

06:42.102 --> 06:44.400
<i>♪ He must be so sad</i>

06:44.471 --> 06:49.238
<i>♪ He goes to extremes
to convince us he's bad</i>

06:49.309 --> 06:51.801
<i>♪ He's really a victim</i>

06:51.878 --> 06:54.279
<i>♪ Of fear and of pride</i>

06:54.347 --> 06:59.979
<i>♪ Look close and there must be
a sweet man inside</i>

07:00.787 --> 07:02.277
- Nah.
- Uh-uh.

07:02.355 --> 07:04.790
<i>♪ There goes Mr. Outrage</i>

07:04.858 --> 07:07.327
<i>♪ There goes Mr. Sneer</i>

07:07.394 --> 07:09.624
<i>♪ He has no time for friends or fun</i>

07:09.696 --> 07:11.824
<i>♪ His anger makes that clear</i>

07:11.898 --> 07:16.665
<i>♪ Don't ask him for a favor
'cause his nastiness increases</i>

07:16.736 --> 07:19.296
<i>♪ No crust of bread for those in need</i>

07:19.372 --> 07:22.239
♪ <i>No</i> cheeses for <i>us</i> "meeces"

07:22.309 --> 07:24.038
Scrooge liked the cold.

07:24.110 --> 07:26.374
He was hard and sharp as a flint.

07:26.446 --> 07:28.278
Secret and self-contained.

07:28.348 --> 07:30.510
As solitary as an oyster.

07:30.584 --> 07:32.882
<i>♪ There goes Mr. Heartless</i>

07:32.953 --> 07:35.149
<i>♪ There goes Mr. Cruel</i>

07:35.222 --> 07:37.782
<i>♪ He never gives
He only takes</i>

07:37.858 --> 07:40.054
<i>♪ He lets his hunger rule</i>

07:40.126 --> 07:44.927
<i>♪ If being mean's a way of life
you practice and rehearse</i>

07:44.998 --> 07:47.467
<i>♪ Then all that work is paying off</i>

07:47.534 --> 07:50.196
<i>♪ 'Cause Scrooge is getting worse</i>

07:50.270 --> 07:54.935
<i>♪ Every day, in every way
Scrooge is getting worse I</i>

07:55.775 --> 07:57.800
- [male] Oh, boy.
- How the time flies.

07:57.878 --> 07:59.812
Look at this, I've got to move...

07:59.880 --> 08:01.541
[horse brays]

08:03.717 --> 08:05.048
Humbug.

08:11.258 --> 08:15.024
Phew! What an unpleasant fellow.

08:15.095 --> 08:20.499
He was a tightfisted hand
at the grindstone, Scroo...

08:20.567 --> 08:23.036
Boy, this really is a dirty city.

08:23.103 --> 08:25.470
Ha. You tellin' me.

08:26.306 --> 08:29.173
[thud, squeaking]

08:29.242 --> 08:31.870
Thank you for making me
a part of this.

08:31.945 --> 08:35.881
He was a tightfisted hand
at the grindstone, Scrooge.

08:35.948 --> 08:40.044
A squeezing, wrenching,
grasping, clutching...

08:40.120 --> 08:42.418
covetous old sinner.

08:42.489 --> 08:44.355
[gulps]

08:44.424 --> 08:46.085
Bob Cratchit?

08:46.159 --> 08:47.354
Yes, Mr. Scrooge?

08:47.427 --> 08:49.156
Who is this?

08:49.229 --> 08:50.856
Mr. Applegate, sir.

08:50.931 --> 08:53.559
He's here to speak to you
about his... mortgage.

08:53.633 --> 08:55.965
Mr. Scrooge,
I know you're very angry about this,

08:56.036 --> 08:58.562
and I didn't mean to
fall behind in the payment.

08:58.638 --> 09:01.005
Lord knows,
it being Christmas and all.

09:01.074 --> 09:03.168
Please don't shout at me, sir.

09:03.243 --> 09:06.269
That and, of course, little Gwen.
Her lungs aren't right.

09:06.346 --> 09:08.610
The doctor takes his share, don't he?

09:08.682 --> 09:10.776
You can yell and scream,
and you're right,

09:10.850 --> 09:12.614
but it won't do no good...

09:12.686 --> 09:15.348
because I'm the stone
you can't squeeze blood from.

09:15.422 --> 09:17.686
And that's the truth!

09:17.757 --> 09:20.055
[Applegate]
Thank you for not shouting at me.

09:20.126 --> 09:22.993
- [door slams]
- [workers] 17... 42...

09:23.063 --> 09:26.522
Let us deal with the eviction notices
for tomorrow, Mr. Cratchit.

09:26.600 --> 09:28.432
Uh...

09:28.501 --> 09:29.969
Tomorrow's Christmas, sir.

09:30.036 --> 09:33.836
Very well, you may gift wrap them.

09:33.907 --> 09:36.399
[worker] Let us help you with that,
Mr. Cratchit.

09:36.476 --> 09:38.740
My, there are certainly a lot today.

09:38.812 --> 09:39.802
We'll get it.

09:39.879 --> 09:42.109
I'm okay, okay.

09:42.182 --> 09:44.116
- Here you go.
- Look out on that end...

09:44.184 --> 09:46.209
[clamoring]

09:46.286 --> 09:48.220
- Uh...
- [workers] Whoa!

09:49.623 --> 09:52.752
Christmas is a very busy time for us,
Mr. Cratchit.

09:52.826 --> 09:56.057
People preparing feasts, giving parties.

09:56.129 --> 09:59.656
Spending the mortgage money
on frivolities.

09:59.733 --> 10:03.431
One might say that December
is the foreclosure season.

10:03.503 --> 10:07.906
Harvest time for the moneylenders.

10:07.974 --> 10:09.499
- Boss, ask him.
- Tell him.

10:09.576 --> 10:12.807
- Come on. Come on.
- Do it now. Do it.

10:12.879 --> 10:15.746
If you please, Mr. Scrooge,
it's gotten colder.

10:15.815 --> 10:19.547
The bookkeeping staff would like to have
an extra shovel of coal for the fire.

10:19.619 --> 10:22.645
- We can't do the bookkeeping.
- Our pens are like ink-cicles.

10:22.722 --> 10:24.554
Our assets are frozen.

10:24.624 --> 10:28.424
How would the bookkeepers
like to be suddenly unemployed?

10:28.495 --> 10:30.327
[all] Heat wave!

10:30.397 --> 10:33.856
[all sing]
This is my island in the sun!

10:33.933 --> 10:37.267
I, I believe you've convinced them
once again, Mr. Scrooge.

10:40.473 --> 10:43.272
At that moment,
who should arrive at the door

10:43.343 --> 10:47.439
but Scrooge's nephew, Fred.
His only living relative.

10:47.514 --> 10:50.006
- Nephew Fred? I don't see him.
- Trust me.

10:51.518 --> 10:53.646
Hello? Uncle?

10:55.855 --> 10:56.845
Rizzo?

10:56.923 --> 10:59.358
You're very good at that, Mr. Dickens.

10:59.426 --> 11:02.691
A merry Christmas, Uncle Scrooge.
God save you.

11:02.762 --> 11:04.355
Merry Christmas?

11:04.431 --> 11:06.695
Bah. Humbug!

11:06.766 --> 11:08.757
Quick, it'll be warmer in there.

11:12.939 --> 11:16.603
Christmas a humbug, Uncle?
You don't mean that, surely.

11:16.676 --> 11:18.701
Actually, I think it's colder in here.

11:18.778 --> 11:21.679
Merry Christmas, you say?
What right have you to be merry?

11:21.748 --> 11:23.238
You're poor enough.

11:23.316 --> 11:25.478
And you to be dismal?
You're rich enough.

11:25.552 --> 11:27.714
He's got him.
The old boy's speechless.

11:27.787 --> 11:29.846
If I could work my will,

11:29.923 --> 11:33.086
every idiot who goes about with
"Merry Christmas" on his lips

11:33.159 --> 11:34.991
would be cooked with his own turkey

11:35.061 --> 11:38.122
and buried with a stake of holly
through his heart.

11:38.198 --> 11:40.030
Well, not quite speechless.

11:40.100 --> 11:41.590
- Uncle...
- Nephew.

11:41.668 --> 11:45.536
You keep Christmas in your own way,
and let me keep it in mine.

11:45.605 --> 11:49.542
Christmas is a loving,
honest and charitable time.

11:49.609 --> 11:53.136
And though it's never put
a scrap of gold or silver in my pocket,

11:53.213 --> 11:55.944
I believe Christmas has done me good
and will do me good,

11:56.015 --> 11:57.676
and I say, God bless it.

11:57.751 --> 11:59.549
[workers cheer]

11:59.619 --> 12:03.453
And how does one celebrate Christmas
on the unemployment line?

12:05.725 --> 12:08.695
Now, in these times,
it was customary on Christmas Eve

12:08.762 --> 12:11.459
for well-meaning gentlemen
to call upon businesses,

12:11.531 --> 12:15.229
collecting donations
for the poor and homeless.

12:15.902 --> 12:17.927
Mr. Scrooge, I presume?

12:18.004 --> 12:19.438
[high-pitched squeak]

12:20.440 --> 12:21.635
Who are you?

12:21.708 --> 12:25.406
We're from the Order of Victoria
Charity Foundation.

12:25.478 --> 12:28.277
We'd like to speak to you
about a donation.

12:28.348 --> 12:30.282
Ah! Welcome!

12:30.350 --> 12:32.944
This jolly old gentleman here
is Mr. Scrooge.

12:33.019 --> 12:35.386
He's very generous to charities.

12:35.455 --> 12:36.980
My dear nephew!

12:37.056 --> 12:40.117
At this festive season of the year,
Mr. Scrooge,

12:40.193 --> 12:44.494
many of us feel we must
take care of our poor and homeless.

12:44.564 --> 12:47.124
Are there no prisons?
No poor houses?

12:47.200 --> 12:49.464
Oh, plenty of those, sir.

12:49.536 --> 12:51.197
Oh. Excellent.

12:51.271 --> 12:53.069
For a moment, I was worried.

12:53.139 --> 12:57.406
Some of us are endeavoring to raise
a fund for the poor and homeless.

12:57.477 --> 12:59.878
What might I put you down for?

12:59.946 --> 13:00.970
Nothing.

13:01.047 --> 13:05.109
- You wish to remain anonymous?
- I wish to be left alone.

13:05.185 --> 13:07.244
I do not make merry myself
for Christmas.

13:07.320 --> 13:08.412
That certainly is true.

13:08.555 --> 13:10.523
I cannot afford
to make idle people merry.

13:10.590 --> 13:12.149
That is certainly not true.

13:12.225 --> 13:14.853
Don't you have other things to do
this afternoon?

13:14.928 --> 13:18.387
Sadly, I do, Uncle.
So I shall make my donation.

13:18.464 --> 13:21.092
And leave you to make yours.

13:21.167 --> 13:22.896
Thank you so very much.

13:22.969 --> 13:27.133
Oh, Uncle, come and have Christmas
dinner with me and Clara tomorrow.

13:27.207 --> 13:29.039
Why ever did you get married?

13:29.108 --> 13:31.133
Why? Because I fell in love.

13:31.211 --> 13:33.236
[laughs]

13:33.313 --> 13:36.578
That's the only thing in the world
sillier than a merry Christmas.

13:36.649 --> 13:39.516
It's no use, I shall keep
my Christmas humor to the last.

13:39.586 --> 13:43.022
A merry Christmas to you.
And a happy New Year.

13:43.089 --> 13:45.490
- Merry Christmas, Fred.
- Merry Christmas, Bob.

13:45.558 --> 13:46.889
Humbug!

13:48.127 --> 13:49.891
[Softly] Ahem.

13:49.963 --> 13:52.364
[clock ticks]

13:58.371 --> 14:01.136
Now, then, sir, about the...

14:01.207 --> 14:02.902
donation.

14:03.610 --> 14:05.476
Well, now.

14:05.545 --> 14:07.274
Let's see.

14:08.514 --> 14:11.506
I know how to treat the poor.

14:11.584 --> 14:15.020
My taxes go to pay for the prisons
and the poorhouses.

14:15.088 --> 14:17.853
- The homeless must go there.
- But some would rather die.

14:17.924 --> 14:20.518
If they'd rather die,
then they'd better do it,

14:20.593 --> 14:22.584
and decrease the surplus population.

14:22.662 --> 14:25.324
- [squeaks]
- Oh, dear. Oh, dear.

14:25.398 --> 14:29.301
This is the door, you may use it.

14:29.369 --> 14:31.235
All right, Beaker, come along.

14:31.304 --> 14:35.241
I think we've taken enough
of Mr. Scrooge's time.

14:35.308 --> 14:38.209
- [Beaker squeaks]
- Oh, dear. Dear, dear.

14:38.278 --> 14:41.942
- [door slams]
- [workers] 17... 24... 58.

14:42.015 --> 14:45.076
<i>♪ Good King Wencelas looked out
on the Feast of Stephen</i>

14:45.151 --> 14:48.348
<i>♪ Though the snow lay round about,
deep and crisp and even</i>

14:48.421 --> 14:51.220
<i>♪ Brightly shone the moon
that... night,</i>

14:51.291 --> 14:52.884
<i>♪ Though... the...</i>

14:52.959 --> 14:54.120
[clears throat]

14:55.094 --> 14:59.361
- What do you want?
- Uh... Penny for the song, guvnor?

15:03.836 --> 15:05.133
[gasps]

15:05.672 --> 15:07.197
Wh... OW!

15:07.941 --> 15:09.067
[groans]

15:10.276 --> 15:11.971
[worker] 17... 24...

15:25.591 --> 15:30.791
[clears throat] Excuse me, Mr. Scrooge,
but it appears to be closing time.

15:31.965 --> 15:36.129
Very well. I'll see you
at eight tomorrow morning.

15:37.403 --> 15:38.734
[workers] Ask him, ask him.

15:38.805 --> 15:40.603
Um... Tomorrow's Christmas.

15:40.673 --> 15:42.971
- 8:30, then.
- [workers sigh]

15:43.042 --> 15:44.441
If you please, sir,

15:44.510 --> 15:47.411
half an hour off hardly seems customary
for Christmas Day.

15:47.480 --> 15:50.415
- [worker] No.
- [worker 2] Hardly customary.

15:50.483 --> 15:53.248
How much time off is customary,
Mr. Cratchit?

15:53.319 --> 15:56.914
Um... Why, um, the, er, whole day.

15:56.990 --> 15:58.856
- Yeah, that's right.
- The whole day.

15:58.925 --> 16:00.290
The entire day?

16:00.360 --> 16:02.385
- No.
- That's the frog's idea.

16:02.462 --> 16:05.557
If you please,
why open the office tomorrow?

16:05.631 --> 16:09.124
Other businesses will be closed.
You'll have no one to do business with.

16:09.202 --> 16:12.661
It'll waste a lot of expensive coal
for the fire.

16:12.739 --> 16:15.902
- That's definitely a point.
- That's a point.

16:15.975 --> 16:19.707
It's a poor excuse for picking
a man's pocket every December the 25th.

16:19.779 --> 16:22.476
[all groan]

16:22.548 --> 16:25.779
But as I seem to be
the only person around who knows that...

16:27.086 --> 16:29.783
- ...take the day off.
- [all cheer]

16:34.293 --> 16:36.523
- Will you stop that?
- [workers yelp]

16:37.930 --> 16:39.921
Thank you, Mr. Scrooge.

16:41.634 --> 16:43.602
Be here all the earlier
the next morning.

16:43.669 --> 16:46.297
- [worker] Okay.
- [worker 2] You bet. First thing.

16:49.609 --> 16:51.771
With their employer gone at last,

16:51.844 --> 16:54.472
Bob Cratchit and the bookkeepers
immediately began

16:54.547 --> 16:59.383
that most pleasant of activities,
the celebration of Christmas.

16:59.452 --> 17:02.422
- He's gone!
- [workers cheer]

17:02.488 --> 17:04.819
Gentlemen, let's close up for Christmas.

17:06.659 --> 17:09.628
<i>♪ There's magic in the air this evening</i>

17:09.694 --> 17:11.823
♪ Magic in the air

17:11.897 --> 17:14.663
<i>♪ The world is at her best, you know</i>

17:14.733 --> 17:17.169
<i>♪ When people love and care</i>

17:17.236 --> 17:21.695
<i>♪ The promise of excitement
is one the night will keep</i>

17:21.773 --> 17:26.712
<i>♪ After all, there's only
one more sleep till Christmas</i>

17:37.590 --> 17:39.490
<i>♪ The world has got a smile</i>

17:39.559 --> 17:42.551
<i>♪ Today, the world has got a glow</i>

17:42.628 --> 17:45.427
<i>♪ There's no such thing as strangers</i>

17:45.498 --> 17:47.523
<i>♪ When a stranger says hello</i>

17:47.600 --> 17:50.126
<i>♪ And everyone is family</i>

17:50.203 --> 17:52.501
<i>♪ We're having so much fun</i>

17:52.572 --> 17:57.510
<i>♪ After all, there's only one
more sleep till Christmas I</i>

17:59.612 --> 18:01.808
Okay, ready. Here we go.

18:16.696 --> 18:18.221
That's it. Ha! Ha!

18:18.297 --> 18:20.288
- [others cheer]
- Mm-hm.

18:22.335 --> 18:24.497
Very good, gentlemen.

18:26.372 --> 18:30.866
<i>♪ 'Tis the season to be jolly and joyous</i>

18:31.844 --> 18:35.280
<i>♪ With a burst of pleasure,
we feel it arrive</i>

18:36.816 --> 18:41.344
<i>♪ It's a season
when the saints can employ us</i>

18:41.420 --> 18:46.290
<i>♪ To spread the news about peace
and to keep love alive</i>

18:46.359 --> 18:47.588
What's that?

18:47.660 --> 18:50.630
Look, it's the penguins'
Christmas skating party.

18:57.503 --> 18:59.471
[quacking]

19:07.213 --> 19:09.409
- Hmm. Ah.
- Look at that!

19:15.888 --> 19:18.016
You did good, boss.

19:18.090 --> 19:21.116
Oh, thank you.
Thank you very much.

19:25.631 --> 19:27.599
WOW!

19:27.667 --> 19:29.897
- No way.
- Come on, Rizzo.

19:34.907 --> 19:35.897
<i>BOY-</i>

19:39.445 --> 19:40.742
Fun, huh?

19:40.813 --> 19:43.111
- Merry Christmas, penguins.
- [all quack]

19:45.384 --> 19:47.785
<i>♪ There's something in the wind today</i>

19:47.853 --> 19:50.447
<i>♪ That's good for everyone</i>

19:50.523 --> 19:53.049
<i>♪ Yes, faith is in our hearts today</i>

19:53.125 --> 19:55.355
<i>♪ We're shining like the sun</i>

19:55.428 --> 19:58.090
♪ And everyone can feel it

19:58.164 --> 20:00.258
<i>♪ The feeling's running deep</i>

20:00.333 --> 20:05.328
<i>♪ After all, there's only
one more sleep till Christmas</i>

20:05.404 --> 20:09.500
<i>♪ After all, there's only one more sleep</i>

20:09.575 --> 20:14.137
<i>♪ Till Christmas Day a'</i>

20:14.213 --> 20:16.204
Merry Christmas!

20:28.661 --> 20:30.151
[dog barks]

20:35.201 --> 20:37.932
Scrooge lived in chambers
which had once belonged

20:38.004 --> 20:41.099
to his old business partners,
Jacob and Robert Marley.

20:41.173 --> 20:43.198
- Have some bread?
- Not while I'm working.

20:43.276 --> 20:45.244
Suit yourself.

20:45.311 --> 20:49.270
The building was a dismal heap of brick
on a dark street.

20:49.348 --> 20:52.613
Once again, you must remember
that the Marleys were dead

20:52.685 --> 20:55.450
- and decaying in their graves.
- Yeuch!

20:55.521 --> 20:57.751
[whispers] That one thing
you must remember,

20:57.823 --> 21:00.258
or nothing that follows
will seem wondrous.

21:00.326 --> 21:01.851
Why are you whispering?

21:01.927 --> 21:04.123
- It's for dramatic emphasis.
- Oh.

21:04.196 --> 21:05.630
Shh.

21:29.522 --> 21:30.853
Jacob Marley?

21:30.923 --> 21:33.119
[booming groan]

21:36.462 --> 21:37.987
You okay?

21:49.041 --> 21:50.372
Humbug.

21:53.379 --> 21:55.848
Oh. Gonzo, speak to me.

21:55.915 --> 21:59.749
I mean, Mr. Dickens.
Charlie! Are you hurt?

21:59.819 --> 22:02.982
To say that Scrooge
was not startled would be untrue.

22:03.055 --> 22:06.491
Still, the moment had passed,
and the world was as it should be.

22:06.559 --> 22:09.119
He ain't hurt.
Didn't even break his concentration.

22:09.195 --> 22:10.924
- Hmm?
- Nothing.

22:15.668 --> 22:18.399
Come on, Rizzo.
We'll follow him in.

22:18.471 --> 22:22.066
In a minute.
I had a bag of jelly beans over here.

22:22.141 --> 22:23.870
Will you just get over here?

22:23.943 --> 22:26.105
- All right.
- Sheesh.

22:27.546 --> 22:29.674
- [Dickens groans]
- Oh-oh.

22:31.417 --> 22:32.543
Steady, steady.

22:32.618 --> 22:35.087
[strangulated]
Scrooge made his way up the stairs,

22:35.154 --> 22:37.145
caring not a button for the darkness.

22:37.223 --> 22:39.783
Darkness was cheap,
and Scrooge liked it.

22:41.961 --> 22:45.693
<i>But the incident at the door
had made Scrooge wary.</i>

22:45.765 --> 22:50.100
<i>Before he shut himself in for the night,
he searched his rooms.</i>

22:50.169 --> 22:52.604
<i>- [Rizzo] Okay, that does it.
- [Dickens] Pardon?</i>

22:52.671 --> 22:54.935
How do you know
what Scrooge is doing?

22:55.007 --> 22:57.203
We're down here and he's up there.

22:57.276 --> 23:01.042
I keep telling you, storytellers
are omniscient. I know everything.

23:01.113 --> 23:04.014
Hoity-toity, Mr. Godlike Smarty-Pants.

23:06.385 --> 23:10.344
To conduct a proper search,
Scrooge was forced to light the lamps.

23:12.091 --> 23:13.820
How does he do that?

23:47.092 --> 23:48.651
Agh!

23:56.669 --> 23:57.966
Oh.

23:59.104 --> 24:01.436
It's my best dressing gown.

24:04.810 --> 24:06.904
No harm done.

24:32.538 --> 24:33.835
[ding]

24:33.906 --> 24:36.238
[clock ticks]

24:36.942 --> 24:38.467
[creaking]

24:44.817 --> 24:46.751
[ringing]

24:57.530 --> 24:59.931
[Scrooge breathes heavily]

25:13.412 --> 25:15.244
[faint clinking]

25:17.716 --> 25:20.208
[laughter]

25:20.286 --> 25:22.983
Look, it's Ebenezer Scrooge.

25:23.055 --> 25:25.786
Looking older and more wicked
than ever.

25:25.858 --> 25:27.917
I knew he wouldn't disappoint us.

25:27.993 --> 25:29.825
[both laugh]

25:32.765 --> 25:33.857
Who are you?

25:33.933 --> 25:35.901
In life, we were your partners,

25:35.968 --> 25:39.233
- Jacob...
- And Robert Marley.

25:39.305 --> 25:41.433
It looks like you.

25:41.507 --> 25:45.444
- But I don't believe it.
- Why do you doubt your senses?

25:45.511 --> 25:48.640
Because a little thing
can affect them.

25:48.714 --> 25:52.207
A slight disorder of the stomach
can make them cheat.

25:52.284 --> 25:56.152
You may be a bit of undigested beef.
A blob of mustard.

25:56.221 --> 25:58.019
A crumb of cheese.

25:58.090 --> 26:01.720
Yes, there's more of gravy
than of grave about you.

26:01.794 --> 26:03.592
[both laugh]

26:04.396 --> 26:06.524
More of gravy than of grave?

26:06.599 --> 26:09.625
What a terrible pun.
Where do you get those jokes?

26:09.702 --> 26:11.864
Leave comedy to the bears, Ebenezer.

26:13.906 --> 26:17.865
Please, Jacob, Robert,
don't criticize me.

26:17.943 --> 26:19.707
You always criticized me.

26:19.778 --> 26:21.610
We were always heckling you.

26:21.680 --> 26:23.614
It's good to be heckling again.

26:23.682 --> 26:25.844
It's good to be doing anything again.

26:27.886 --> 26:29.581
Why do you come to me?

26:29.655 --> 26:34.559
<i>♪ We're Marley and Marley
Avarice and greed</i>

26:34.627 --> 26:39.360
<i>♪ We took advantage of the poor,
just ignored the need-y</i>

26:39.431 --> 26:43.834
<i>♪ We specialized in causing pain,
spreading fear and doubt</i>

26:43.902 --> 26:48.203
<i>♪ And if you could not pay the rent,
we simply threw you out</i>

26:49.608 --> 26:52.634
There was the year
we evicted the entire orphanage.

26:52.711 --> 26:56.909
I remember the little tykes
all standing in the snowbank.

26:56.982 --> 26:59.815
With their little
frostbitten teddy bears.

27:03.522 --> 27:07.925
<i>♪ We're Marley and Marley
Our hearts were painted black</i>

27:07.993 --> 27:10.587
<i>♪ We should have known our evil deeds</i>

27:10.663 --> 27:13.257
<i>♪ Would put us both in shack-fies</i>

27:13.332 --> 27:17.599
<i>♪ Captive, bound, we're double-ironed,
exhausted by the weight</i>

27:17.670 --> 27:20.162
<i>♪ As freedom comes from giving love</i>

27:20.239 --> 27:22.571
<i>♪ So prison comes with hate</i>

27:22.641 --> 27:24.769
♪ We're Marley and Marley

27:24.843 --> 27:27.676
[make ghostly noises]

27:27.746 --> 27:29.737
♪ We're Marley and Marley

27:31.583 --> 27:34.985
But my friends, you were not unfeeling
towards your fellow men.

27:35.054 --> 27:38.319
True, there was something
about mankind we loved.

27:38.390 --> 27:40.154
I think it was their money.

27:40.225 --> 27:42.319
[Marley Brothers laugh]

27:42.394 --> 27:46.695
<i>♪ Doomed, Scrooge
You're doomed for all time</i>

27:46.765 --> 27:51.498
<i>♪ Your future is a horror story
Written by your crime</i>

27:51.570 --> 27:56.337
<i>♪ Your chains are forged
by what you say and do</i>

27:56.408 --> 27:59.002
<i>♪ So have your fun
When life is done</i>

27:59.078 --> 28:00.910
<i>♪ A nightmare waits for you</i>

28:02.314 --> 28:04.248
Why these terrible chains?

28:04.316 --> 28:07.013
- [both wail]
- The chains.

28:07.086 --> 28:11.114
We forged these chains in life
by our acts of greed.

28:11.190 --> 28:13.318
You wear such a chain yourself.

28:13.392 --> 28:16.157
Humbug. Speak comfort to me, friends.

28:16.228 --> 28:17.696
Comfort!

28:17.763 --> 28:19.561
[both wail]

28:19.631 --> 28:22.430
You will be haunted by three spirits.

28:22.501 --> 28:24.765
Haunted?
I've already had enough of that.

28:24.837 --> 28:29.035
Without these visits, you cannot hope
to avoid the path we tread.

28:29.108 --> 28:32.601
Expect the first ghost tonight,
when the bell tolls one.

28:32.678 --> 28:35.045
Can't I meet them all at once
and get it over with?

28:35.114 --> 28:38.243
When the bell tolls one!

28:38.317 --> 28:40.308
♪ We're Marley and Marley

28:40.385 --> 28:42.854
[Wail]

28:42.921 --> 28:45.185
♪ We're Marley and Marley

28:45.257 --> 28:47.521
[Wail]

28:47.593 --> 28:50.119
♪ We're Marley and Marley ♪

28:50.195 --> 28:51.924
[ghosts wail]

28:53.499 --> 28:55.024
[Marleys] Change!

28:56.201 --> 28:58.363
[clock ticks]

29:06.378 --> 29:10.542
And with that, the spirits of Scrooge's
partners vanished into the darkness,

29:10.616 --> 29:15.417
leaving him once again
alone in his room.

29:15.487 --> 29:19.583
That's scary stuff. Should we be worried
about the kids in the audience?

29:19.658 --> 29:22.093
No, it's all right. This is culture.

29:22.161 --> 29:25.096
Jelly bean? I had them
in my pocket all along.

29:25.164 --> 29:26.563
[groans]

29:26.632 --> 29:27.622
What?

29:40.012 --> 29:41.343
Humbug.

29:42.481 --> 29:44.279
Come on.

29:44.349 --> 29:45.976
But I really hate this.

29:46.051 --> 29:48.019
You wanted to know
what was happening.

29:48.086 --> 29:51.522
Scrooge's bedchamber
is on this side of the house. Jump.

29:51.590 --> 29:54.218
There's only two things
in this life I hate.

29:54.293 --> 29:56.523
Heights, and jumping from them.

29:56.595 --> 29:58.825
Too late now.
Come on, I'll catch you.

29:58.897 --> 30:00.661
[whimpers]

30:00.732 --> 30:03.064
God save my little broken body.

30:03.135 --> 30:05.126
[screams]

30:09.608 --> 30:11.474
- Missed.
- [growls]

30:11.543 --> 30:14.240
Wait a second.
I forgot my jelly beans.

30:14.313 --> 30:15.371
Um...

30:23.222 --> 30:24.314
What?

30:24.389 --> 30:26.221
You can fit through those bars?

30:26.291 --> 30:27.816
Yeah.

30:27.893 --> 30:29.292
You are such an idiot.

30:29.361 --> 30:31.295
What, what? Hey, what?

30:31.864 --> 30:33.093
What?

30:33.165 --> 30:34.690
[Rizzo whispers] What?

30:40.105 --> 30:42.039
[Scrooge breathes heavily]

30:43.575 --> 30:45.339
[ticking]

30:48.547 --> 30:50.140
[Rizzo] Oh, dear.

30:50.215 --> 30:54.584
Scrooge slipped into the empty silence
of a dreamless sleep.

30:54.653 --> 30:58.112
You know, a guy could break his tail
falling out of this tree.

30:58.190 --> 31:00.181
Want to see what's going on, don't you?

31:00.259 --> 31:02.387
- Yes.
- There's Scrooge's window.

31:02.461 --> 31:04.259
Oh, yeah.

31:04.329 --> 31:06.161
[clock ticks]

31:06.965 --> 31:09.127
[clock whirs, chimes]

31:15.908 --> 31:17.307
[ding]

31:23.415 --> 31:28.478
Expect the first ghost
when the bell tolls one!

31:31.290 --> 31:33.019
Wow! Ouch.

31:54.479 --> 31:57.779
Are you the spirit
whose coming was foretold to me?

31:57.849 --> 31:59.078
I am.

31:59.151 --> 32:03.645
But... you're just a child.

32:03.722 --> 32:06.885
I can remember nearly 1,900 years.

32:06.959 --> 32:10.122
I am the Ghost of Christmas Past.

32:10.195 --> 32:11.959
What business has brought you here?

32:12.030 --> 32:14.727
- Your welfare.
- Huh.

32:14.800 --> 32:17.462
A night's unbroken rest
might aid my welfare.

32:17.536 --> 32:19.732
Your salvation, then.

32:19.805 --> 32:22.502
Take heed. Come.

32:27.379 --> 32:31.282
I beg you, spirit, I am mortal.
I'm liable to fall.

32:31.350 --> 32:34.684
A touch of my hand, and you shall fly.

32:42.594 --> 32:44.585
- What are we doing?
- Nothing.

32:44.663 --> 32:46.290
- What?
- Just hold on.

32:46.365 --> 32:48.459
[Rizzo screams]

32:50.969 --> 32:53.529
- Watch out, Rizzo.
- What? Oh!

32:53.605 --> 32:56.631
[Dickens laughs] Whee!

32:57.309 --> 32:59.107
Hello, London!

32:59.177 --> 33:01.202
[Rizzo] Goodbye, lunch!

33:02.347 --> 33:04.907
[pants] Spirit?

33:05.684 --> 33:06.810
Yes'?

33:06.885 --> 33:08.580
Nothing.

33:10.389 --> 33:12.687
- Look, Rizzo.
- I don't want to look.

33:12.758 --> 33:15.557
Spirit? What is that light?

33:17.129 --> 33:18.995
It cannot be dawn.

33:19.064 --> 33:21.362
[spirit] It is the past.

33:24.503 --> 33:27.131
Look, it's beautiful, Rizzo.

33:27.205 --> 33:29.503
[Rizzo] Mommy!

33:36.648 --> 33:38.639
Hey, we're going down.

33:39.251 --> 33:41.686
Hang on, Rizzo.

33:41.753 --> 33:44.450
- [woman screams]
- [Dickens] Sorry, madam.

33:44.523 --> 33:46.457
- [man grunts]
- [Rizzo] Pardon me, sir.

33:46.525 --> 33:48.357
[Dickens] Look out, Rizzo.

33:51.463 --> 33:53.557
Rizzo, this is Louise.

33:53.632 --> 33:55.623
Yeah, we've met.

34:04.810 --> 34:09.407
And so they arrived
in Ebenezer Scrooge's childhood.

34:09.481 --> 34:11.882
That was the worst trip of my life.

34:11.949 --> 34:13.315
It's over now.

34:13.385 --> 34:16.446
- Yeah, safe at last.
- [meows]

34:17.289 --> 34:18.279
No.

34:18.989 --> 34:21.458
No. No! Oh, no!

34:21.525 --> 34:22.925
Nice kitty, nice kitty.

34:22.994 --> 34:25.018
Ow! I'm from New Jersey.

34:25.097 --> 34:26.792
[cat meows, kids shout]

34:27.833 --> 34:30.324
It was the afternoon of Christmas Eve,

34:30.402 --> 34:33.702
and Scrooge was conscious
of a thousand odors.

34:33.772 --> 34:38.869
Each one connected with a thousand
thoughts, hopes, joys and cares,

34:38.944 --> 34:41.106
long, long forgotten.

34:43.281 --> 34:45.272
It's my old school.

34:46.217 --> 34:47.844
I was a boy here.

34:48.853 --> 34:51.482
That's Henry.

34:51.556 --> 34:53.820
And Edmund, my best friend.

34:53.891 --> 34:56.520
Hello, boys. Hello.

34:56.594 --> 34:59.360
These are but shadows
of your past, Ebenezer.

34:59.431 --> 35:02.059
They can neither see nor hear you.

35:02.134 --> 35:04.466
Come, let us go inside.

35:06.838 --> 35:08.829
Rizzo, stop playing with the cat.

35:08.907 --> 35:11.604
- Save me, save me!
- [cat meows viciously]

35:30.195 --> 35:33.631
And what a flood of memories
came back to him,

35:33.698 --> 35:36.827
as Scrooge beheld his old classroom.

35:37.869 --> 35:39.997
I know it all so well, spirit.

35:40.972 --> 35:42.701
The desks.

35:43.909 --> 35:45.968
The smell of the chalk.

35:48.380 --> 35:50.576
I chose my profession in this room.

35:50.649 --> 35:53.380
And is he, too, familiar?

35:56.354 --> 36:00.018
[Dickens] Scrooge beheld a small boy,
a boy he knew,

36:00.091 --> 36:02.560
oh, very well indeed.

36:05.497 --> 36:08.091
Good heavens.

36:08.166 --> 36:09.725
It's me.

36:09.801 --> 36:12.236
Come Ebenezer,
the last coach is leaving.

36:12.304 --> 36:14.602
Come on,
he never goes home for Christmas.

36:14.673 --> 36:17.005
Who cares about stupid old Christmas?

36:18.977 --> 36:21.139
I was often alone.

36:22.347 --> 36:25.977
More time for reading... and study.

36:26.051 --> 36:29.988
The Christmas holiday was a chance
to get some extra work done.

36:31.122 --> 36:33.887
A time for... solitude.

36:37.028 --> 36:39.395
Rats don't understand these things.

36:39.464 --> 36:41.592
You were never a lonely child?

36:41.666 --> 36:45.102
I had 1,274 brothers and sisters.

36:45.170 --> 36:49.164
Sheesh.
Rats don't understand these things.

36:49.241 --> 36:52.768
Let us see another Christmas
in this place.

36:52.844 --> 36:55.006
They were all very much the same.

36:57.449 --> 36:59.213
Nothing ever changed.

36:59.284 --> 37:01.378
You changed.

37:22.173 --> 37:24.870
[Dickens] The years performed
their terrible dance.

37:24.943 --> 37:29.107
And in a moment, Scrooge had seen
his entire childhood pass.

37:29.180 --> 37:33.344
He saw his old school room
age and decay.

37:33.418 --> 37:35.250
What the... Hey!

37:35.320 --> 37:36.310
Agh!

37:36.388 --> 37:40.256
So, Master Scrooge, graduation day!

37:41.359 --> 37:44.522
That's my old headmaster.

37:44.596 --> 37:46.792
This man taught me my greatest lesson.

37:46.865 --> 37:50.324
Stand up. Build your life
as this school was built.

37:50.402 --> 37:51.460
Push!

37:51.536 --> 37:53.527
[strains] My ear, my ear, my ear.

37:55.540 --> 38:00.637
Yes, work hard, work long,
and be constructive.

38:00.712 --> 38:03.647
Ebenezer, life is a golden opportunity.

38:03.715 --> 38:06.650
Today you go forth into the real world.

38:06.718 --> 38:09.619
You must keep your nose
to the grindstone.

38:09.688 --> 38:11.952
Work hard, lad. And one day,

38:12.023 --> 38:15.015
your life will be as solid
as this very building.

38:16.961 --> 38:19.521
Hmm. I've been meaning
to fix that shelf.

38:19.597 --> 38:20.826
Yes, headmaster.

38:20.899 --> 38:25.962
Young man, you have been apprenticed
to a fine company in London.

38:26.037 --> 38:29.996
Today, you become a man of business.

38:30.075 --> 38:32.066
I'm looking forward to it, headmaster.

38:32.143 --> 38:34.578
You will love business.

38:34.646 --> 38:36.910
It is the American way.

38:36.981 --> 38:37.971
Sam?

38:38.049 --> 38:40.518
<i>'</i> Mmm?
- [Whispers]

38:41.486 --> 38:44.148
Oh. It is the British way.

38:44.222 --> 38:45.212
Good.

38:45.290 --> 38:47.156
Yes, headmaster.

38:51.096 --> 38:53.428
[headmaster]
Oh, here is your coach, Ebenezer.

38:53.498 --> 38:56.832
Come, Scrooge, there is much to see.

38:58.536 --> 39:00.527
Remember, don't tip the driver.

39:09.114 --> 39:13.210
A moment later, Scrooge found himself
standing on a city street,

39:13.284 --> 39:17.380
looking at a building
he had not seen in years.

39:17.455 --> 39:20.618
Tell me, Ebenezer Scrooge,
do you know this place?

39:20.692 --> 39:24.185
Know it? My first job was here.

39:24.262 --> 39:26.924
This is Fozziwig's
old rubber chicken factory.

39:26.998 --> 39:28.796
Once again, it was Christmas Eve,

39:28.867 --> 39:33.930
night was falling, and the lamplighters
were plying their trade.

39:34.005 --> 39:37.464
Hey, light the lamp, not the rat.
Light the lamp, not the rat!

39:37.542 --> 39:39.306
- My apologies.
- What are you doing?

39:39.377 --> 39:41.607
Put me out, put me out!

39:41.679 --> 39:44.114
- Rizzo!
- What?

39:44.182 --> 39:46.082
[screams]

39:46.151 --> 39:47.482
[gurgling]

39:47.552 --> 39:50.749
[shivers]
Oh, oh, Th-th-th-thank you.

39:50.822 --> 39:52.551
You're welcome.

39:54.926 --> 39:57.657
There he is, old Fozziwig himself.

39:57.729 --> 40:01.393
Look my lads, dusk has fallen,
and the lamplighters are at work.

40:01.466 --> 40:03.696
It's Christmas Eve for certain.

40:03.768 --> 40:05.736
What an employer he was.

40:05.804 --> 40:09.172
As hard and as ruthless
as a rose petal.

40:09.240 --> 40:11.504
It's time for the party to begin.

40:11.576 --> 40:14.204
It's the Fozziwig Christmas party.

40:14.279 --> 40:15.974
Rizzo, come on.

40:16.948 --> 40:19.212
Rizzo, just grab hold of the stick.

40:19.284 --> 40:21.548
Merry Christmas.

40:21.619 --> 40:23.610
Thank you, thank you.

40:25.089 --> 40:27.888
Excuse me, everyone.
Can we have some quiet, please?

40:27.959 --> 40:29.984
[clucking]

40:30.829 --> 40:32.092
Whoa!

40:38.303 --> 40:41.000
I suppose I should be grateful for that.

40:41.072 --> 40:42.938
You're welcome.

40:43.007 --> 40:46.204
Everyone, please,
can I have your attention for a moment?

40:46.277 --> 40:47.267
[they laugh]

40:47.345 --> 40:50.576
Look, it's the Marley brothers.

40:50.648 --> 40:52.776
My old partners, as they were as lads.

40:52.851 --> 40:55.218
Can I have your attention, please?

40:55.286 --> 40:56.811
[chatter continues]

40:58.923 --> 41:00.789
Quiet!

41:02.861 --> 41:04.226
Thank you.

41:04.295 --> 41:05.922
That's better.

41:05.997 --> 41:09.297
Welcome to Fozziwig and Mom's
annual Christmas party.

41:09.367 --> 41:11.233
At this time in the proceedings,

41:11.302 --> 41:14.135
it is a tradition
for me to make a little speech.

41:14.205 --> 41:16.936
And it's a tradition for us
to take a little nap.

41:17.008 --> 41:19.272
[they laugh]

41:19.344 --> 41:21.472
Uh, pay no attention to them.

41:21.546 --> 41:24.572
My speech,
here is my Christmas speech.

41:24.649 --> 41:28.210
"Thank you all
and merry Christmas."

41:28.286 --> 41:30.380
- That was the speech?
- That was dumb.

41:30.455 --> 41:32.184
- It was obvious.
- It was pointless.

41:32.257 --> 41:34.419
It was short.

41:34.492 --> 41:37.018
[both] I loved it! [both laugh]

41:37.095 --> 41:41.362
I'm bored with speeches.
Let's dance, Son!

41:41.432 --> 41:43.901
Here's Mrs. Fozziwig to start the party.

41:43.968 --> 41:46.494
- Way to go, Ma!
- Hit it, boys!

41:46.571 --> 41:48.232
